'''Artur Gustav Martin Phleps''' (29 November 1881&nbsp;– 21 September 1944) was an [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]], [[Kingdom of Romania|Romanian]] and [[Nazi Germany|German]] army officer who held the rank of ''[[Obergruppenführer|SS-Obergruppenführer und General der Waffen-SS]]'' (lieutenant general) in the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' during [[World War II]]. An [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] officer before and during [[World War I]], he specialised in [[mountain warfare]] and [[logistics]], and had been promoted to ''[[Oberstleutnant]]'' (lieutenant colonel) by the end of the war. During the [[interwar period]] he joined the [[Romanian Army]], reaching the rank of ''General-locotenent'' (major general), and also became an adviser to [[Carol II of Romania|King Carol]]. After he spoke out against the government, he was sidelined and requested to be dismissed from the army.

In 1941 he left Romania and joined the ''Waffen-SS'' as a ''SS-[[Standartenführer]]'' (colonel) under his mother's maiden name of Stolz. Seeing action on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] as a regimental commander with the [[5th SS Panzergrenadier Division Wiking|SS Motorised Division ''Wiking'']], he later raised and commanded the [[7th SS Volunteer Mountain Division Prinz Eugen|7th SS Volunteer Mountain Division ''Prinz Eugen'']], raised the [[13th Waffen Mountain Division of the SS Handschar (1st Croatian)|13th Waffen Mountain Division of the SS ''Handschar'' (1st Croatian)]], and commanded the [[V SS Mountain Corps]]. Units under his command committed many crimes against the civilian population of the [[Independent State of Croatia]], [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia]] and [[Italian governorate of Montenegro]].{{sfn|Lopičić|2009|pp=26–30}}{{sfn|Lopičić|2009|pp=112–113}} His final appointment was as plenipotentiary general in south [[Transylvania|Siebenbürgen]] and the [[Banat (1941–44)|Banat]], during which he organised the evacuation of the ''[[Volksdeutsche]]'' (ethnic Germans) of Siebenbürgen to the Reich. In addition to the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]], Phleps was awarded the [[German Cross|German Cross in Gold]], and after he was killed in September 1944, he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves|Oak Leaves]] to his Knight's Cross.

==Early life==
[[File:Kirchenburg Birthälm.jpg|thumb|left|Phleps' birthplace of Birthälm in  Siebenbürgen (modern-day [[Transylvania]])|alt=rural village landscape with old church steeple in the mid-distance and terraced hills in the background]]
Phleps was born in [[Biertan|Birthälm]] (Biertan), near [[Sibiu|Hermannstadt]] in [[Transylvania|Siebenbürgen]], then a part of the [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] (modern-day [[Romania]]).{{sfn|Glaise von Horstenau|1980|p=204}} At the time, Siebenbürgen was densely populated by [[Germans of Romania|ethnic Germans]] commonly referred to as [[Transylvanian Saxons]]. He was the third son of the surgeon Gustav Phleps and Sophie (née Stolz), the daughter of a peasant. Both families had lived in Siebenbürgen for centuries.{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=96}}{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=8–9}} After finishing at the Lutheran ''[[Realschule]]'' school in Hermannstadt,{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=96}} Phleps entered the [[Imperial and Royal]] cadet school in [[Bratislava|Pressburg]] (in modern-day [[Slovakia]]) in 1900, and on 1 November 1901 was commissioned as a ''[[Leutnant]]'' (lieutenant) in the 3rd Regiment of the ''[[County of Tyrol|Tiroler]] [[Gebirgsjäger|Kaiserjäger]]'' (mountain infantry).{{sfn|Glaise von Horstenau|1980|p=204}}{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}}

In 1903, Phleps was transferred to the 11th ''Feldjäger'' (rifle) Battalion in [[Kőszeg|Güns]] (in modern-day [[Hungary]]),{{sfn|Glaise von Horstenau|1980|p=204}} and in 1905 was accepted into the [[Theresian Military Academy]] in [[Wiener Neustadt]]. He completed his studies in two years, and was endorsed as suitable for service in the [[Staff (military)|General Staff]]. Following promotion to ''[[Oberleutnant]]'' (first lieutenant) he transferred to the staff of the 13th Infantry Regiment at [[Osijek|Esseg]] in [[Slavonia]], and then the 6th Infantry Division in [[Graz]]. This was followed by a promotion to ''[[Hauptmann]]'' (captain) in 1911 along with a position on the staff of the XV [[Corps|Army Corps]] in [[Sarajevo]], where he specialised in [[mobilisation]] and [[military communications|communications]] in the difficult terrain of [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]] and [[Herzegovina]].{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=8–9}}{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}}

==World War I==
At the outbreak of [[World War I]], Phleps was serving with the staff of the 32nd Infantry Division in [[Budapest]]. The division was involved in the early stages of the [[Serbian Campaign (World War I)|Serbian campaign]], during which Phleps was transferred to the [[Operations (military staff)|operations staff]] of the Second [[Field army|Army]]. The Second Army was soon withdrawn from the Serbian front and deployed via the [[Carpathian Mountains]] to the Austro-Hungarian province of [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria|Galicia]] (modern-day [[Poland and Ukraine]]) to defend against a successful offensive by the [[Russian Empire]]. The Second Army continued to fight the Russians in and around the Carpathians through the winter of 1914–1915. In 1915 Phleps was again transferred, this time to ''Armeegruppe Rohr'' commanded by ''[[General of the Cavalry (Germany)|General der Kavallerie]]'' (General) [[Franz Rohr von Denta]], which was formed in the [[Carinthia (state)|Austrian Alps]] in response to the [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] declaration of war in May 1915. ''Armeegruppe Rohr'' became the basis for the formation of the [[10th Army (German Empire)|10th Army]], which was headquartered in [[Villach]]. Phleps subsequently became the deputy [[quartermaster]] of the 10th Army, responsible for organising the supply of the troops fighting the Italians in the mountains.{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}}{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=9}}

On 1 August 1916, Phleps was promoted to ''[[Major (Germany)|Major]]''.{{sfn|Glaise von Horstenau|1980|p=204}} Later that month, King [[Ferdinand of Romania]] led the [[Kingdom of Romania]] in joining the [[Triple Entente]], and subsequently invaded Phleps' homeland of Siebenbürgen. On 27 August, Phleps became the chief of staff of the 72nd Infantry Division, which was involved in Austro-Hungarian operations to repel the Romanian invasion. He remained in this theatre of operations for the next two years, ultimately serving as the chief quartermaster of the German [[9th Army (German Empire)|9th Army]],{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=9}} and was awarded the [[Iron Cross]] 2nd Class on 27 January 1917.{{sfn|Thomas|1998|p=154}} In 1918 he returned to the mountains when he was transferred to ''Armeegruppe Tirol'', and ended the war as an ''[[Oberstleutnant]]'' (lieutenant colonel) and chief quartermaster for the entire [[Italian Front (World War I)|Alpine Front]].{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}}{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=9}}

==Between the wars==
After the war the Austro-Hungarian Empire [[Austria-Hungary#Dissolution|was dissolved]], and Phleps returned to his homeland, which had become part of Romania under the [[Treaty of Trianon]]. He joined the [[Romanian Land Forces|Romanian Army]] and was appointed as commander of the Saxon National Guard, a [[militia]] formed from the German-speaking people of Siebenbürgen. In this role he opposed the Hungarian communist revolutionary government of [[Béla Kun]], which [[Hungarian–Romanian war of 1919|fought Romania in 1919]]. During a battle at the [[Tisza]] river against Kun's forces he disobeyed direct orders and was subsequently [[court-martial]]led. The trial concluded that Phleps had saved the Romanian forces through his actions, and he was promoted to ''[[Oberst]]'' (colonel).{{sfn|Bergel|1972|p=87}} He commanded the 84th Infantry Regiment, then joined the general staff and taught [[Military logistics|logistics]] at the [[Carol I National Defence University|War Academy]] in [[Bucharest]]. He attended the V Army Corps [[staff college]] in [[Brașov|Kronstadt]], and published a book, ''Logistics: Basics of Organisation and Execution'', in 1926 which became the standard work on logistics for the Romanian Army.{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=9–10}}{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=229}} Ironically, after the book was published, Phleps failed his first general's examination on the topic of logistics.{{sfn|Bergel|1972|p=88}} He commanded various Romanian units, including the 1st Brigade of the ''[[vânători de munte]]'' (mountain troops) and also acted as a military advisor to King [[Carol II of Romania|Carol II]] in the 1930s.{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=9–10}}{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=229}} Phleps reached the rank of ''Generalleutnant'' (major general) despite his disdain for the corruption, intrigue and hypocrisy of the royal court.{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|pp=100–101}} After criticising government policy{{sfn|Bergel|1972|p=89}} and publicly calling King Carol a liar when another general tried to twist his words,{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=101}} he was transferred to the reserves in 1940 and dismissed from the service at his own request in 1941.{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}}

==World War II==

===SS Motorised Division ''Wiking''===
In November 1940, with the support of the leader of the ''Volksgruppe in Rumänien'' (ethnic Germans in Romania), Andreas Schmidt, Phleps had written to the key ''Waffen-SS'' recruiting officer ''SS-[[Brigadeführer|Brigadeführer und Generalmajor der Waffen SS]]'' (Brigadier) [[Gottlob Berger]] offering his services to the Third Reich. Phleps subsequently asked for permission to leave Romania to join the ''[[Wehrmacht]]'', and this was approved by the recently installed Romanian ''[[Conducător]]'' (dictator) General [[Ion Antonescu]].{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=101}} Phleps volunteered for the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' instead,{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=10}} enlisting under his mother's maiden name of Stolz.{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}} According to the historian Hans Bergel, Phleps joined the ''Waffen-SS'' because ''Volksdeutsche'' were not permitted to join the ''Wehrmacht''.{{sfn|Bergel|1972|p=92}} He was appointed as a ''SS-[[Standartenführer]]'' (colonel) by ''[[Reichsführer-SS]]'' [[Heinrich Himmler]] and joined the [[5th SS Panzer Division Wiking|SS Motorised Division ''Wiking'']],{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=10}} where he commanded Dutch, Flemish, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish and Finnish volunteers.{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}} When [[Hilmar Wäckerle]], the commander of SS-Regiment ''Westland'', was killed in action near [[Lvov]] in late June 1941, Phleps took over command of that regiment. Phleps distinguished himself in the fighting at [[Kremenchuk]] and [[Dnipropetrovsk]] in the Ukraine, commanded his own ''[[Kampfgruppe]]'',{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=45}} became a [[confidant]] of ''[[Generalmajor]]'' (Brigadier General) [[Hans-Valentin Hube]], commander of the [[16th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|16th Panzer Division]], and was subsequently promoted to ''SS-[[Oberführer]]'' (senior colonel).{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=10}} In July 1941 he was awarded the 1939 clasp to his Iron Cross (1914) 2nd Class and then the Iron Cross (1939) 1st Class.{{sfn|Thomas|1998|p=154}}

===7th SS Volunteer Mountain Division ''Prinz Eugen''===
On 30 December 1941, ''[[Generalfeldmarschall]]'' (Field Marshal) [[Wilhelm Keitel]] advised Himmler that [[Adolf Hitler]] had authorised the raising of a seventh ''Waffen-SS'' division from the ''Volksdeutsche'' (ethnic Germans) of Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Stein|1984|p=170}} In the meantime, Phleps reverted to his birth name from his mother's maiden name. Two weeks later, ''SS-Brigadeführer und Generalmajor der Waffen SS'' Phleps was selected to organise the new division.{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=10}} On 1 March 1942, the division was officially designated the ''SS-Freiwilligen-Division "Prinz Eugen"''.{{sfn|Stein|1984|p=170}} Phleps was promoted to ''SS-[[Gruppenführer|Gruppenführer und Generalleutnant der Waffen SS]]'' (major general) on 20 April 1942. After recruitment, formation and training in the [[Banat (1941–44)|Banat]] in October 1942, the two regiments and supporting arms were deployed into the southwestern part of the [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia]] as an anti-[[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisan]] force. Headquartered in [[Kraljevo]], with its two mountain infantry regiments centred on [[Užice]] and [[Raška, Serbia|Raška]], the division continued to train. Some artillery batteries, the anti-aircraft battalion and the motorcycle battalion and cavalry squadron continued to form in the Banat.{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=19–21}} During his time with the 7th SS Division, Phleps was referred to as "Papa Phleps" by his troops.{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=231}}

[[File:Artur Phleps and Kurt Waldheim.jpg|250px|thumb|From left: Italian General Ercole Roncaglia, [[Kurt Waldheim]], ''Oberst'' (Colonel) Macholz and Phleps (with briefcase) at Podgorica airfield in Montenegro during Case Black, 22 May 1943. This photograph caused much controversy when it was published while Waldheim was [[Austrian presidential election, 1986|running for the Austrian presidency in 1985–1986]].|alt=an Italian officer and three German officers in uniform standing beneath the wing of an aircraft on a grassed airfield]]

In early October 1942, the division commenced Operation ''Kopaonik'', targeting the [[Chetnik]] force of Major [[Dragutin Keserović]] in the [[Kopaonik|Kopaonik Mountains]], which ended with little success, as the Chetniks had forewarning of the operation and were able to avoid contact. After a quiet winter, in January 1943 Phleps deployed the division to the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (NDH) to participate in [[Case White]].{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=27–28}} Between 13 February and 9 March 1943 he was responsible for the initial aspects of raising the [[13th Waffen Mountain Division of the SS Handschar (1st Croatian)|13th Waffen Mountain Division of the SS ''Handschar'' (1st Croatian)]] in the NDH in addition to his duties commanding the 7th SS Division.{{sfn|Lepre|1997|pp=20–24}}
In his strongly apologetic divisional history of the division which he later commanded,{{sfn|Casagrande|2003|p=25}} [[Otto Kumm]] claims that the division captured [[Bihać]] and [[Bosanski Petrovac]], killed over 2,000 Partisans and captured nearly 400 during Case White.{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=30–40}} After a short rest and refit in April, the division was committed to [[Case Black]] in May and June 1943, during which it advanced from the [[Mostar]] area into the [[Italian governorate of Montenegro]] and killed, according to Kumm, 250 Partisans and captured over 500.{{sfn|Kumm|1995|pp=43–53}} The historian Thomas Casagrande notes that all German units fighting partisans routinely counted the civilians they had murdered as partisans. Therefore it can be assumed that the reported number of inflicted casualties included many civilians.{{sfn|Casagrande|2003|p=255}} The division played a decisive role during the fighting. Although Himmler had already planned to award Phleps with the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] for his role in organising the 7th SS Division, it was for the achievements of his division during Case Black that Phleps received the award. Phleps was also portrayed in the SS-magazine ''[[Das Schwarze Korps]]''.{{sfn|Casagrande|2003|p=255}} He received the Knight's Cross in July 1943,{{sfn|Bishop|Williams|2003|p=186}} while he was also promoted to ''Obergruppenführer und General der Waffen-SS'' (lieutenant general),{{sfn|Glaise von Horstenau|1980|p=204}} and placed in command of the [[V SS Mountain Corps]].{{sfn|Stein|1984|p=210}}

In May 1943, Phleps became frustrated by the failure of his Italian allies to cooperate with German operations, which was demonstrated in his reputation for forthright speech. During a meeting with his Italian counterpart in [[Podgorica]], Montenegro, Phleps called the Italian corps commander General [[Ercole Roncaglia]] a "lazy macaroni".{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=236}} Phleps scolded his ''Wehrmacht'' interpreter, ''Leutnant'' [[Kurt Waldheim]] for toning down Phleps' language, saying, "Listen Waldheim, I know some Italian and you are not translating what I am telling this so-and-so".{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=236}} On another occasion, Phleps threatened to shoot Italian sentries who were delaying his passage through a checkpoint.{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=237}} On 15 May 1943, Phleps handed over command of the division to ''SS-Brigadeführer und Generalmajor der Waffen SS'' [[Karl von Oberkamp]].{{sfn|Kumm|1995|p=55}}

While under Phleps' command, the division committed many crimes against the civilian population of the NDH, especially during Case White and Case Black.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|pp=154 & 161}} These included "burning villages, massacre of inhabitants, torture and murder of captured partisans", and the division thereby developed a distinctive reputation for cruelty.{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=231}} These charges have been denied by Kumm, among others. But the divisional orders routinely called for the annihilation of hostile civilian population and documents by the ''Waffen-SS'' themselves show that these orders were put into practice. For example, Himmler's police representative in the NDH, ''SS-Brigadeführer und Generalmajor der Polizei'' [[Konstantin Kammerhofer]], reported on 15 July 1943 that units of the 7th SS Division had shot the Muslim population of [[Košutica, Sokolac|Kosutica]], about 40 men, women, and children gathered in a "church". The division claimed that "bandits" in the village had opened fire, but the police could not discover any traces of combat. Such incidents, which jeopardized the plan to raise a Muslim SS division, led to a dispute between Kammerhofer and Phleps' successor Oberkamp. Himmler ordered Phleps to intervene and Phleps reported on 7 September 1943 that he could not discover anything wrong with the shootings in Kosutica and that Kammerhofer and Oberkamp had resolved their dispute.{{sfn|Casagrande|2003|pp=258-260}} The war crimes committed by the 7th SS Division became the subject of international controversy when Waldheim's service in the Balkans became public in the mid-1980s, during his successful bid for the [[President of Austria|Austrian presidency]].{{sfn|Rosenbaum|Hoffer|1993|pp=32 & 79}}

===V SS Mountain Corps===

The formations under the command of V SS Mountain Corps varied during Phlep's command. In July 1944, it consisted of the [[118th Jäger Division (Wehrmacht)|118th Jäger Division]] and [[369th (Croatian) Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|369th (Croatian) Infantry Division]] in addition to the 7th SS and 13th SS divisions. Throughout Phlep's command, the corps was under the overall control of [[2nd Panzer Army]] and conducted anti-Partisan operations throughout the NDH and Montenegro.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=71 & 147}} These operations included Operations [[Operation Kugelblitz|''Kugelblitz'']] (ball lightning) and ''Schneesturm'' (blizzard), which were part of a major offensive in eastern Bosnia in December 1943, but they were only a limited success.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=398}} Phleps had met personally with Hitler to discuss the planning for Operation ''Kugelblitz''.{{sfn|Lumans|2012|p=238}}

Due to the unreliable nature of the troops loyal to the NDH government, Phleps utilised Chetnik forces as auxiliaries, stating to a visiting officer that he could not disarm the Chetniks unless the NDH government provided him with the same strength in reliable troops.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=310}} In January 1944, due to fears that the [[Western Allies]] would invade along the [[Dalmatia]]n coastline and islands, V SS Mountain Corps forced the mass evacuation of male civilians between the ages of 17 and 50 from that area. Phleps was criticised by both NDH and German authorities for the harshness with which the evacuation was carried out.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=319–320}} During the first six months of 1944, elements of the V SS Mountain Corps were involved in Operation ''Waldrausch'' (Forest Fever) in central Bosnia,{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|pp=181–189}} [[13th Waffen Mountain Division of the SS Handschar (1st Croatian)#Anti-Partisan operations March to May 1944|Operation ''Maibaum'']] (Maypole) in eastern Bosnia,{{sfn|Lepre|1997|p=187}} and [[Operation Rösselsprung (1944)|Operation ''Rösselsprung'']] (Knight's Move), the attempt to capture or kill the Partisan leader [[Josip Broz Tito]].{{sfn|Eyre|2006|p=373–376}}

On 20 June 1944, Phleps was awarded the [[German Cross]] in Gold.{{sfn|Thomas|1998|p=154}} In September, he was appointed [[plenipotentiary]] general of German occupation troops in south Siebenbürgen and the [[Banat (1941–44)|Banat]], organising the flight of the ''Volksdeutsche'' of north Siebenbürgen ahead of the advancing [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]].{{sfn|Bergel|1979|p=46}}

==Death and aftermath==

While en route to a meeting with Himmler in Berlin, Phleps and his entourage made a detour to reconnoitre the situation near [[Arad, Romania]] after receiving reports of Soviet advances in that area. Accompanied only by his adjutant and his driver, and unaware of the presence of Red Army units in the vicinity, he entered [[Șimand]], a village approximately {{convert|20|km}} north of Arad, on the afternoon of 21 September 1944. Soviet forces were already in the village, and Phleps and his men were captured and brought in for interrogation. When the building in which they were held was attacked by German aircraft later that afternoon, the prisoners tried to escape and were shot by their guards.{{sfn|Bergel|1972|p=106}} Bergel suspects that Phleps had been set up by Hungarian army officers who had found out that Phleps knew of plans for Hungary to switch sides as Romania had done shortly before.{{sfn|Bergel|1972|p=104}} Phleps' personal effects, including his identity card, tags and decorations, were found by a Hungarian patrol and handed over to German authorities on 29 September 1944. Phleps had been listed as missing in action since 22 September 1944 when he did not show up for his meeting with Himmler, who had issued a warrant for Phleps' arrest.{{sfn|Schulz|Zinke|2008|p=511}}

Phleps was posthumously awarded the Oak Leaves to his Knight's Cross on 24 November 1944,{{sfn|Williamson|2004|p=121}} which was presented to his son, ''[[SS-Obersturmführer]]'' (First Lieutenant) Dr.med. Reinhart Phleps,{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=105}} a battalion doctor serving in the 7th SS Division.{{sfn|Schulz|Zinke|2008|p=551}}{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=15}} Soon after his death, the 13th ''Gebirgsjäger'' Regiment of the 7th SS Division was given the [[cuff title]] ''Artur Phleps'' in his honour.{{sfn|Windrow|1992|p=14}} Phleps was married; his wife's name was Grete and in addition to their son Reinhart, they had a daughter, Irmingard.{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=111}} One of Phleps' brothers became a doctor, and the other was a professor at the [[Gdańsk|Danzig]] technical university, now [[Gdańsk University of Technology]].{{sfn|Kaltenegger|2008|p=96}}

==Accusations of war crimes==
Phleps was accused by the Yugoslav authorities of war crimes in association with the atrocities committed by 7th SS Division in the area of [[Nikšić]] in [[Montenegro]] during Case Black. At the [[Nuremberg trials]] on 6 August 1946, a document from the Yugoslav State Commission for Crimes of Occupiers and their Collaborators regarding the crimes of the 7th SS Division was quoted as follows:{{sfn|Nuremberg Trial proceedings}}

<blockquote>At the end of May 1943 the division came to Montenegro to the area of Niksic in order to take part in the fifth enemy offensive in conjunction with the Italian troops. [...] The officers and men of the SS division ''Prinz Eugen'' committed crimes of an outrageous cruelty on this occasion. The victims were shot, slaughtered and tortured, or burnt to death in burning houses. [...] It has been established from the investigations entered upon that 121 persons, mostly women, and including 30 persons aged 60–92 years and 29 children of ages ranging from 6 months to 14 years, were executed on this occasion in the horrible manner narrated above. The villages [and then follows the list of the villages] were burnt down and razed to the ground. [...] For all of these most serious War Crimes those responsible besides the actual culprits--the members of the SS Division Prinz Eugen--are all superior and all subordinate commanders as the persons issuing and transmitting the orders for murder and devastation. Among others the following war criminals are known: SS Gruppenfuehrer and Lieutenant General of the Waffen-SS Phleps; Divisional Commander, Major General of the Waffen-SS Karl von Oberkamp; Commander of the 13th Regiment, later Divisional Commander, Major General Gerhard Schmidhuber...</blockquote>

==Awards==
Phleps received the following awards during his service:

* Austrian [[Military Merit Medal (Austria-Hungary)|Military Merit Medal]] (''Signum Laudis'')
** in Bronze with war decoration and swords on 13 October 1914{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
** in Silver with war decoration on 15 March 1916{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* Austrian [[Military Merit Cross (Austria-Hungary)|Military Merit Cross]] 3rd Class with war decoration and swords on 3 July 1915{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* [[Decoration for Services to the Red Cross]] 2nd Class with war decoration on 23 October 1915{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* Prussian Iron Cross (1914) 2nd Class on 27 January 1917{{sfn|Thomas|1998|p=154}}
* Austrian [[Order of the Iron Crown (Austria)|Order of the Iron Crown]] 3rd Class with war decoration and swords on 24 April 1917{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* Officers cross of the [[Order of Franz Joseph]] with war decoration and swords on 23 July 1918{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* [[Order of the Star of Romania]]
** Officers cross with swords on ribbon of military merit on 12 March 1920{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
** Commanders cross on 28 February 1933{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* [[Czechoslovak War Cross 1918|Czechoslovak War Cross]] on 1 March 1928{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* [[Order of the Yugoslav Crown]] 2nd Class in 1933{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* Bulgarian [[Order of Military Merit (Bulgaria)|Order of Military Merit]] 2nd Class on 26 April 1934{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* Romanian [[Order of the Crown (Romania)|Order of the Crown]]
** Commander on 1 January 1927{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
** Grand Cross on 10 May 1939{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* Clasp to the Iron Cross (1939) 2nd Class on 10 July 1941{{sfn|Thomas|1998|p=154}}
* Iron Cross 1st Class on 26 July 1941{{sfn|Thomas|1998|p=154}}
* [[Infantry Assault Badge]] in Bronze on 7 November 1943{{sfn|Thomas|Wegmann|1994|p=149}}
* German Cross in Gold on 20 June 1944 as ''SS-Obergruppenführer und General der Waffen-SS'' in the V SS Mountain Corps{{sfn|Patzwall|Scherzer|2001|p=351}}
* [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves]]
** Knight's Cross on 4 July 1943 as ''SS-Brigadeführer und Generalmajor der Waffen SS'' and commander of SS-Division "Prinz Eugen"{{sfn|Fellgiebel|2000|pp=338, 499}}{{refn|1=According to Scherzer as commander of SS-Volunteer-Mountain-Division "Prinz Eugen".{{sfn|Scherzer|2007|p=593}}|group="Note"}}
** 670th Oak Leaves on 24 November 1944 (posthumously) as ''SS-Obergruppenführer und General der Waffen-SS'', commanding general of the V SS Mountain Corps and [[SS and Police Leader|Higher SS and Police Leader]] as well as [[commander-in-chief]] in Siebenbürgen.{{sfn|Scherzer|2007|p=593}}{{sfn|Fellgiebel|2000|p=93}}

